answer:
To solve the problem, you need to know something about the variation in the bushels of yield per acre. Suppose from past records you know the yields of wheat possess a range of approximately 10 bushels per acre. You could then approximate $\sigma_1=\sigma_2=\sigma$ by letting the range equal $4 \sigma$. Thus,

$$
\begin{aligned}
4 \sigma & \approx 10 \text { bushels } \\
\sigma & \approx 2.5 \text { bushels }
\end{aligned}
$$


The next step is to solve the equation

$$
z_{\alpha / 2} \sigma_{\left(\bar{x}_1-\bar{x}_2\right)}=\mathrm{ME} \quad \text { or } \quad z_{\alpha / 2} \sqrt{\frac{\sigma_1^2}{n_1}+\frac{\sigma_2^2}{n_2}}=\mathrm{ME}
$$

for $n$, where $n=n_1=n_2$. Because we want the estimate to lie within $\mathrm{ME}=.25$ of ( $\mu_1-\mu_2$ ) with confidence coefficient equal to .95 , we have $z_{\alpha / 2}=z_{.025}=1.96$. Then, letting $\sigma_1=\sigma_2=2.5$ and solving for $n$, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
1.96 \sqrt{\frac{(2.5)^2}{n}+\frac{(2.5)^2}{n}} & =.25 \\
1.96 \sqrt{\frac{2(2.5)^2}{n}} & =.25 \\
n & =768.32 \approx 769 \text { (rounding up) }
\end{aligned}
$$


Consequently, you will have to sample 769 acres of wheat for each fertilizer to estimate the difference in mean yield per acre to within .25 bushel.
